That is, not only our psychological and emotional institutions,

59:08.000 --> 59:11.000
everything related to the type of personality,

59:12.000 --> 59:16.000
remember, the theory of personality of Freud, Jung, Bern,

59:17.000 --> 59:21.000
what we have already studied, but also sociocultural factors.

59:22.000 --> 59:26.000
The psychological mechanisms of perception in intergroup communication

59:27.000 --> 59:32.000
are related to the process of so-called social stereotyping.

59:32.000 --> 59:37.000
The essence of this is that the perception of a certain person's image

59:38.000 --> 59:42.000
is based on certain type schemes.

59:43.000 --> 59:45.000
I will give you a simple example.

59:46.000 --> 59:49.000
For 10 years I have been teaching at various universities.

59:50.000 --> 59:52.000
And students come to my first course.

59:53.000 --> 59:57.000
Here is a very noticeable effect of social stereotyping.

59:57.000 --> 01:00:01.000
Let's take students of recent years.

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:08.000
Because social stereotyping differs from students of 5, 7 and 10 years ago.

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:14.000
It turns out that a student who wears a certain brand of certain clothes,

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:20.000
Prada, Gucci, Chanel, Versace, drives a certain brand of a car,

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:24.000
is perceived by the group as more successful,

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:28.000
more intelligent and more intellectually developed student.

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:33.000
All other students, who, according to their intellectual characteristics,

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:39.000
may outperform those above, are not perceived by the group.

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:43.000
Everything is equated to the second and third courses,

01:00:44.000 --> 01:00:46.000
when people enter into closer relations,

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:49.000
and when the effect of the initial perception,

01:00:50.000 --> 01:00:52.000
that is, the attitude of a person to a certain group

01:00:52.000 --> 01:00:55.000
due to social stereotyping, ceases to work,

01:00:56.000 --> 01:01:00.000
then, accordingly, other characteristics come to the forefront,

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:06.000
and, accordingly, other students become smarter, more intellectual.

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:09.000
However, the important characteristics,

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:13.000
those that allow to attribute a partner or a person to a certain group,

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:16.000
are quite precise.

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:19.000
That is, in terms of how a person dresses,

01:01:19.000 --> 01:01:22.000
what manner of behavior he has, how he talks,

01:01:23.000 --> 01:01:27.000
we, in the initial perception, attribute him to a certain group.

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:29.000
This is true.

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:31.000
However, the mistake is different.

01:01:32.000 --> 01:01:35.000
We refine the other features of the personality,

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:38.000
the intellect of this person,

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:40.000
and here we make a mistake,

01:01:41.000 --> 01:01:44.000
because we can overestimate the personality of a person,

01:01:45.000 --> 01:01:46.000
or vice versa,

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:49.000
by some certain factors that he does not have,

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:51.000
we can underestimate him.

01:01:52.000 --> 01:01:57.000
Thus, these initial perception mistakes are due to three main factors.

01:01:58.000 --> 01:02:03.000
These are superiority, attractiveness, and attitude to us.

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:06.000
So, the perception scheme is as follows.

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:11.000
Each of us has important criteria for us,

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:15.000
and information about superiority is usually

01:02:16.000 --> 01:02:19.000
embedded in clothes and manner of behavior.

01:02:20.000 --> 01:02:24.000
For example, I have a certain inner criterion,

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:28.000
I have a car of a certain class, of a certain value,

01:02:29.000 --> 01:02:34.000
and my inner criterion is that a person who drives the same car as me is successful,

01:02:35.000 --> 01:02:39.000
and if he drives a car of a higher class and more expensive,

01:02:39.000 --> 01:02:41.000
he is even more successful.

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:44.000
Therefore, all people who fall into my field of view,

01:02:45.000 --> 01:02:50.000
who drive other cars of a higher class and more expensive,

01:02:51.000 --> 01:02:53.000
I tend to overestimate them.

01:02:54.000 --> 01:02:58.000
It seems to me that they are smarter, better, stronger, and more successful.

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:02.000
However, if a person falls into my field of view,

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:06.000
who has a car of a lower class, or does not have a car at all,

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:09.000
I tend to underestimate him.

01:03:10.000 --> 01:03:15.000
It seems to me that he is less successful, less intelligent, less interesting.

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:18.000
I repeat, this is a perception error.

01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:24.000
There are certain social stereotypes that we attribute to the class,

01:03:25.000 --> 01:03:31.000
while we underestimate or overestimate other deeper personal characteristics.

01:03:32.000 --> 01:03:37.000
Now let's see how the attractiveness factor works in life.

01:03:38.000 --> 01:03:42.000
The attractiveness factor is, as noted in psychology,

01:03:43.000 --> 01:03:47.000
a beautiful, I quote, and ugly appearance.

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:53.000
It is that we also, focusing on the beautiful and ugly appearance of a person,

01:03:54.000 --> 01:03:59.000
we tend to overestimate or underestimate his personal characteristics.

01:03:59.000 --> 01:04:02.000
Once there was an interesting experiment.

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:06.000
Teachers were offered the personal affairs of their students

01:04:07.000 --> 01:04:10.000
in order to assess their intellectual abilities,

01:04:11.000 --> 01:04:16.000
their abilities, their relationship with peers, and some plans for the future.

01:04:17.000 --> 01:04:22.000
The whole trick of the experiment was that there was one personal affair,

01:04:23.000 --> 01:04:26.000
but it was pasted on by different photos of different children.

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:30.000
There were photos of beautiful children and ugly children.

01:04:31.000 --> 01:04:34.000
It is interesting that as a result of this experiment,

01:04:35.000 --> 01:04:40.000
all personal affairs with photos of beautiful children received the highest marks

01:04:41.000 --> 01:04:44.000
and the highest promising prospects for development.

01:04:45.000 --> 01:04:50.000
Photos with the personal affairs of children on which ugly children were pasted,

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:54.000
I quote, and ugly children received low marks

01:04:55.000 --> 01:04:58.000
and low opportunities and prospects for development.

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:04.000
So, attractiveness is not only our individual personal impression,

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:09.000
but, as psychologists have proven, it also has a social nature.

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:15.000
And the third factor that is a companion of information distortion and perception

01:05:16.000 --> 01:05:18.000
is the factor of attitude to us.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:24.000
In fact, everything that indicates agreement and disagreement of a partner with us.

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:28.000
A lot of different experiments were also conducted here,

01:05:29.000 --> 01:05:32.000
and, accordingly, a group of people perceived the lecturer.

01:05:33.000 --> 01:05:37.000
If the opinion of the lecturer coincided with the group of participants,

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:44.000
the lecturer was perceived as successful, intellectual, his own, as a relative soul.

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:49.000
If the opinion of the lecturer did not coincide with the opinion of the group of participants,

01:05:50.000 --> 01:05:57.000
it was strange and it was customary to underestimate the intellectual and personal characteristics of the lecturer.

01:05:58.000 --> 01:06:01.000
He was not perceived as his own, and, accordingly,

01:06:02.000 --> 01:06:05.000
the attitude to this lecturer in the group was completely different

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:08.000
than that whose opinion coincided with the group.

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:17.000
Thus, we have just considered three key factors that affect the primary perception,

01:06:18.000 --> 01:06:20.000
that is, in the process of primary contact.

01:06:21.000 --> 01:06:25.000
So, it is attractiveness, superiority and attitude to us.

01:06:26.000 --> 01:06:29.000
However, when people enter into a longer, longer contact,

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:33.000
completely different perception factors act here,

01:06:34.000 --> 01:06:38.000
such as identification, empathy and reflection.

01:06:39.000 --> 01:06:46.000
Now we will consider the psychological mechanisms of perception and understanding in the process of constant communication.

01:06:47.000 --> 01:06:52.000
These are three components — identification, empathy and reflection.

01:06:53.000 --> 01:06:55.000
What is identification?

01:06:56.000 --> 01:06:58.000
It is an assimilation of oneself to another person.

01:06:59.000 --> 01:07:01.000
That is, in the process of interaction,

01:07:02.000 --> 01:07:07.000
people are accustomed to putting themselves in the place of another person and predict,

01:07:08.000 --> 01:07:12.000
how I would act in the place of this person if…

01:07:13.000 --> 01:07:16.000
In the book by Dale Carnegie, How to Influence People,

01:07:17.000 --> 01:07:19.000
the process of identification is described very well,

01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:23.000
that is, the ability to put oneself in the place of another person,

01:07:24.000 --> 01:07:26.000
how I would act in this situation.

01:07:26.000 --> 01:07:30.000
The next point of perception is empathy.

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:34.000
Empathy is an understanding not at the level of thoughts,

01:07:35.000 --> 01:07:37.000
how I would act, but at the level of feelings.

01:07:38.000 --> 01:07:42.000
It is an attempt to emotionally respond to the problems of another person.

01:07:43.000 --> 01:07:46.000
The founder of the humanistic psychology, Rogers,

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:48.000
once spoke about empathy,

01:07:49.000 --> 01:07:53.000
that it is the ability to enter into the feelings of another person

01:07:53.000 --> 01:07:58.000
and live them as another person lives them.

01:07:59.000 --> 01:08:05.000
Well, the feeling of empathy is a very serious psychological load,

01:08:06.000 --> 01:08:10.000
because if we live through the emotional state of all the people

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:12.000
we encounter in life,

01:08:13.000 --> 01:08:15.000
there is a syndrome of burnout,

01:08:16.000 --> 01:08:17.000
especially among those employees,

01:08:18.000 --> 01:08:19.000
those categories of employees,

01:08:20.000 --> 01:08:22.000
who are associated with communication with clients,

01:08:23.000 --> 01:08:26.000
support services, call centers, operators,

01:08:27.000 --> 01:08:32.000
those professions that are associated with constant interaction

01:08:33.000 --> 01:08:35.000
with the problems of other people.

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:39.000
Therefore, the level of their empathy is very strictly controlled

01:08:40.000 --> 01:08:41.000
at the level of skill training,

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:47.000
because if you go deep into the problem of each client,

01:08:48.000 --> 01:08:49.000
accordingly, I repeat,

01:08:50.000 --> 01:08:52.000
it is a very serious psychological load.

01:08:53.000 --> 01:08:57.000
And people, as a rule, burn out very quickly during the year,

01:08:58.000 --> 01:09:00.000
they have such a stress syndrome.

01:09:01.000 --> 01:09:05.000
And the third point of perception and understanding is reflexion,

01:09:06.000 --> 01:09:09.000
it is the awareness of the acting individual

01:09:10.000 --> 01:09:13.000
of how he is perceived by the partner in communication.

01:09:14.000 --> 01:09:17.000
That is, if at the level of empathy and identification

01:09:18.000 --> 01:09:22.000
we are trying to understand the feelings of others or thoughts of others,

01:09:23.000 --> 01:09:26.000
then at the level of reflexion we are not only trying to understand the feelings and thoughts of others,

01:09:27.000 --> 01:09:33.000
but also to build a scheme of how another person perceives me after that.

01:09:34.000 --> 01:09:37.000
That is, such a double reflection of actions of each other.

01:09:38.000 --> 01:09:41.000
Actually, these three main psychological mechanisms

01:09:42.000 --> 01:09:44.000
lie at the base of perception and understanding

01:09:45.000 --> 01:09:49.000
when longer relationships are established.

